<HEADLINE>
Wood&#39;s Search for the Holy Bard
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<POST>
<POSTER> Paul Crowley </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2003-07-03T24:21:00 </POSTDATE>

Our American cousins have been spared sight of this TV
monstrosity for a few brief weeks. How lucky they are.

It's actually quite interesting -- in a perverse sort of way.
It's the very B E S T that Strats can produce -- and it's
an abomination. It has as much to do with history as
Monty Python's &quot;Search for the Holy Grail&quot;, and as much
to do with reality as &quot;Buffy -- Vampire Slayer&quot;.

Image after image is introduced with a straight face and
a straight lie -- and there is not the slightest pretence at
qualification. It's history by a seven-year old for other
seven-year-olds, none of whom have yet got near the
idea of 'evidence'. A more truthful story could be told
about Father Christmas and his reindeer -- and it would
be told in the same fatuous tones: &quot;Hey, what story
can I think of next -- anything will do for the kind of
idiots that are likely to be watching this . . . . &quot;.

It will destroy whatever reputation Wood had acquired as
an historian.

We have no evidence that the Stratman actually attended
the local school, but that does not stop Wood describing
in the most minute detail how he spent his time there,
including: &quot; . . . One day Master Hunt showed him a book
on poetry -- it was Arthur Golding's translation of Ovid . . &quot;.

It's Bible stories for infants. Of course, Wood's complete
naivety comes out in this instance. More informed
Stratfordians would keep away from that topic. They'd
know that Arthur Golding was the maternal uncle of the
main opposition candidate, and that &quot;he did the
translation&quot; while living in the same house -- when
Oxford was in his mid-teens.

Another story: &quot; . . Shakespeare's parents took him to
Coventry to see the Mystery plays . .&quot;. Somehow Wood
forgets to mention that Coventry is nearly 20 miles from
Stratford, a good two days walk for a child.

As I mentioned in another post (not responded to by any
Strat, of course) he claims that Shakespeare used all
manner of local Warwickshire terms; the falsity of each
claim can be readily exposed by glancing at the OED.
He says that a 'kecksie' is a child's whistle, and he picks
a blade of grass and blows it to show how. But he forgot
to read Henry V where the word is used:
But hateful docks, rough thistles, kecksies, burs,
Losing both beauty and utility.

Children's whistles fit in that context as well as pig's
ears. This is about as good an illustration of the quality
of Wood's &quot;research&quot; as any.

You can only produce an account of the life of the
Stratman as Shakespeare if you are determined to
ignore -- or grossly misinterpret -- every word of the
canon. Wood is well set down that road.

Paul.

