I must assume that you have not read pages 17 and 18 of Wood's book, where
he precisely does not say that a kecksie &quot;is&quot; a whistle. 'Kecksie' is a
blade of the rough couch-grass with which children still make piercing
whistle sounds. (In H5 it is to be understood in its basic sense, as a
'hateful' weed for which the farmer has to keep an eye open and a spade
ready.) Wood gives further examples of surviving Warwickshire dialect words
and expressions also found in Shakespeare.

