The plant Wood plucked and used as a whistle was not Heracleum, which in my
Shropshire youth was 'cow parsley', properly 'hogweed': it has large leaves
and thick but hollow stems that children use as pea-shooters. We confused
it, I think, with a different but not dissimilar-looking plant that blooms a
little earlier, the true cow parsley, which has feathery leaves. Both are
common wayside plants, and look splendid along a country road when in full
bloom. (Hogweed is not to be confused with the much larger and poisonous
giant hogweed, which causes agonising burns on the mouth to any child who
tries it as a pea-shooter.)

I don't know for certain what the &quot;Henry V&quot; passage means by 'kecks', or
whether Wood was correct is saying that 'kecksie' is the Warwickshire name
for couch-grass, but that's what he plucked in the TV programme, and it is a
nasty weed. The blades are sharp-edged, as children who have cut themselves
while whistling have painfully found out.

Alan Jones

