What did Coventry need that Stratford had -- or
vice versa? Such townlands were self-sufficient,
growing their own food, brewing their own beer,
spinning their own wool, weaving their own cloth,
making their own clothes, own furniture, etc. etc.
Take a look at a map of England and you will
see some good roads, still in existence since
the Romans -- Fosse Way (not far from Stratford
and Coventry), Icknield Street, Watling Street,
and so on. But towns seem to ignore them.
They didn't need such roads. Their economies
were not geared into any serious long-distance
transport. If there was a port or a major market
for their produce, good roads would have been
maintained -- as, say, feeding into London.
But there was nothing like that around Warwick.
They would have 'exported' some livestock --
on the hoof -- but little else.

