Whether, as Wood said, WS was taken by his parents to Coventry we don't, and
probably can't, know. It's a reasonable deduction, however: internal
evidence from the Works indicates that he was acquainted with the Mystery
plays; there was little likelihood of his ever seeing a script; the plays
were suppressed when he was in his teens; little boys are unlikely to travel
eighteen miles and back unaccompanied. Put all that together, and Wood's
statement
seems sensible enough.

You are rather hard on Wood's TV series, especially for someone who insists
on so extraordinary an interpretation of the Sonnets, depending on what to
the rest of us seem wild surmises and forced double-meanings. Wood is not
engaged in original scholarship, but in using visual means to suggest what
lay behind the creation of the Works; he takes a fundamentally orthodox
view, and would not have been given four hour-long slots if he had hummed
and hawed with &quot;might&quot; and &quot;perhaps&quot; and &quot;conceivably&quot;.

The book is more cautious, but is again not an attempt at ground-breaking
research. He simply summarises, and brilliantly illustrates, what
specialists have to say: in his lengthy list of Further Reading he mentions
especially Schoenbaum, Honan and Duncan-Jones on WS's life.

Alan Jones

