In 1592, the actor Simon Jewell made his will (Prerogative Court
of Canterbury 63 Harrington, proved 23 August 1592), in which
he made bequests to various &quot;fellows&quot; in the acting company
in which he was a sharer. Jewell itemized the various sums of money
that were owed to him as well as his debts to others. The first
two items among the sums owed to Jewell were as follows:

&quot;Imprimis due vnto me Simon Iewell from my fellowes for my share
of apparrell the somm of thirteene pounde six shillinges eighte
pence. Item more due unto me from my fellowes the sixth parte
of thirtie seaven pounde wch amounteth to six pounds three
shillinges fouer pence, and haue paide my share for horses
waggen and apparrell newe boughte.&quot;

Thus, the sharers in this company shared the costs of
&quot;horses waggen and apparrell&quot;. I don't know why they
would split up the cost of a &quot;waggen&quot; unless they used
it to travel from town to town.

There are plenty of other references to travelling players
using carts or wagons to carry their costumes and props,
but this is the most explicit one I could put my hand to
quickly. It will make absolutely no difference to Crowley,
of course, but I thought I would post it for the
benefit of others.

