Thanks for that, Robert.

Among the ~200 carriers we have these which indicate
wheeled transport:
Bury (Suffolk) wagons -- Thursdays
Cambridge -- wagons or coaches
come on Thursdays and Fridays
Chelmsford (Essex) -- wagon -- come Wednesday
Chippenganger (Essex) -- wagons -- come Wednesday
Dunmow (Essex) -- wagons -- come Wednesday
Hertford town -- wagon or coach come every Friday
Hadham (Herts) -- carrier or wagon
come and go Mon, Tues, Fri, Sat;
Hatfield -- wagon or coach -- come every Friday
Gloucestershire (sundry places) -- wains or wagons --
every week at the Swan
Ingarstone (Essex) -- wains -- come Wednesdays
Saffron Walden (Essex) -- wagon -- at The Bull on
Tues, Wednesdays
St. Albans -- coach -- arrives Fridays, leaves Tuesdays
Stock (Essex) -- wains -- come Wednesdays
Watford -- wagon -- Thursdays
Winchester -- wagon -- Thursdays
Ware -- wagon -- Friday and Saturday

We must remember that this 'schedule' comes from
the providers -- and like the modern British railway
system -- would often represent hopes rather than
expectations. Many of the services seem to me to
be combined -- for example, there are a suspiciously
large number of services out of Essex arriving on
Wednesdays.

Likewise, the 'wagon or coach' to Hatfield, Hertford
and Cambridge on Fridays is IMO probably the same
one -- since Hatfield and Hertford are on (or close to)
the route to Cambridge. It probably also covers the
wagon to Ware on Fridays.

Only one coach service, as such, is offered -- that to
St Albans. Since wagons are very different from
fully sprung coaches, I think we get a feeling for the
way in which both were regarded as forms of
personal transport -- i.e. people much preferred
horseback

Allowing for a certain amount of exaggeration, this list
provides a useful snapshot of the transport system
of 1637. That's sixty years after our date (of &quot;Shake-
speare's parents taking young William to Coventry&quot;) --
but I doubt if the road system had changed much in
that time. In summary: carriers (i.e. packhorses) were
the standard system. Only where roads were good --
mostly those radiating from London for a distance
of about 50 miles -- would we expect to find any
regular wheeled traffic.

Paul.

