Just in case you wanted to know...

Quartermasters in the American Civil War considered six mules to have
the hauling power of four horses. A packmule's load was limited to
about 200 pounds, but when the cargo was in wagons, the regulation
load for a six-mule team was 4,000-4,500 lbs. on a macadamized road;
3,000-3,500 lbs. on a solid dirt road; 1,800-2,500 lbs. on a dirt
track in rough country. The wagon also held several hundred pounds of
grain to feed the team, not counted in the load weight. So wagons
would start to be attractive if the cargo was over 1,000 lbs. or too
bulky for saddlepacking. (Source: E. Hagerman, &quot;The American Civil
War and the Origins of Modern Warfare&quot;)

