Of course it doesn't make much difference to the subject of this
argument whether the wool ever left Warwickshire, since Crowley claims
that transportation of this sort of goods on Warwickshire roads was
impossible (unless he expects us to believe in a rather impractical
*VERY* long train of packhorses). Even if the Warwickshire shepherd
sent the wool from his Warwickshire farm directly to John Shakespeare,
then it would have had to travel down the same Warwickshire roads.
The fact that the Warwickshire shepherd was selling his wool in a
London market, however, proves that he was willing to ship to London
(had it been purchased by a customer from London or Kent, for example
- there is no point of going all the way to a London market to sell
your wool if you are *only* willing to sell to a Warwickshire
neighbour). This means that the wool either made the journey from
Warwickshire to London to be sold, or would have made that journey if
a London buyer had appeared (both of which destroy Crowley's claims
about the extent of travel, trade, and transport in the Renaissance).

I would suggest, without having any firm evidence for my beliefs, that
it would have been cheaper and easier for John Shakespeare, having
purchased this huge quantity of wool with the intention of reselling
it, to move it to the buildings that he owned in Stratford (and part
of his own house has traditionally been known as the &quot;woolshop&quot;),
since a three-day journey by (hired?) wagons would be much cheaper
than the hire or purchase of a London warehouse for weeks or months
until a resale was arranged.

