Perhaps I misled you by saying the services were in alphabetical order
of destination. Strictly, they are in order of origin, of the towns to
which the carriers belonged. So &quot;The Carriers of St. Albans&quot; means
those men who have the profession of carrier who live at St Albans. It
does follow that they would be going to St Albans, but also that they
are distinct from the carriers of any other place, even if it was on
the way to St Albans or St Albans was on the way to it. I do not think
the duplication you posit is real.

In his introduction, Taylor expressly says he does not include
connecting services or possible drops on the way: &quot;Others may object
and say that I have not named all the towns and places that Carriers
do go unto in England and Wales. To whom I yield; but yet I answer,
that if a Carrier of York hath a letter or goods to deliver at any
town in his way thither, he serves the turn well enough: and there are
Carriers and Messengers from York to carry such goods and letters as
are too be passed any ways north, broad and wide as far or farther
than Berwick.&quot;

There was generally a number of carriers at any one place, as is shown
by the odd exception when Taylor says something like &quot;The Carrier of
Coggeshall in Suffolk doth lodge at the Spread Eagle in Gracious
street. He comes and goes on Thursdays and Fridays.&quot; Carriers from the
same town, or district, came and went together in a crowd - obviously
enough - for protection and help on the way and for directions, there
being no sign-posts. So in I Henry IV act 2 scene 1, the second
carrier addresses the first with &quot;Come, neighbour Mugs&quot;.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="

&gt;Only one coach service, as such, is offered -- that to
&gt;St Albans. Since wagons are very different from
&gt;fully sprung coaches, I think we get a feeling for the
&gt;way in which both were regarded as forms of
&gt;personal transport -- i.e. people much preferred
&gt;horseback

"/>

There are several types of transport distinguished, and at least one I
would expect to see that is not.
&quot;Clothiers do come every week out of divers parts of Gloucestershire
to the Saracen's Head in Friday street.
The Wains or Waggons do come every week from sundry places in
Cloucestershire, and are to be had at the Swan near Holborn Bridge.&quot;
(From Gloucester to London is 109 miles by today's roads.)

I assume clothiers had some special kind of transport that meant they
could take some return loads for the public but not others. I don't
know what that would be. Pack-horses would seem suitable, but other
carriers too used pack-horses; those in I Henry IV are not clothiers.

Coach-horses were harnessed abreast, but waggon-horses in tandem.
(Pepys' Diary, 1 Nov. 1662, with Latham and Matthews' note and their
Companion volume under 'Travel'). That enabled waggons to use narrower
roads, or roads where the passable part was narrower. &quot;The waggons
carried goods for the most part, but also provided rough and ready
accommodation for passengers. Pepys thought them good enough for his
parents and sister and servants, but not for himself and Elizabeth.&quot;
(Companion).

How a wain differed from a waggon I do not know. (If Taylor means
they are the same, then he also means a waggon is the same as a
coach.) They are separately defined by the Shorter Oxford:

Waggon (1523). 1. A strong four-wheeled vehicle designed for the
transport of heavy goods. 2. A carriage of any kind for the conveyance
of persons, their luggage, etc. (last in 1638). 3. An open
four-wheeled vehicle built for carrying hay ... (1573). 4. A covered
vehicle for the regular conveyance of commodities and passengers by
road (1615). (5-8 are too late.)

Wain (the older word). 1. A large open vehicle, usu. four-wheeled,
drawn by horses or oxen, and used for carrying heavy loads, esp. of
agricultural produce. (2. is Ursa Major.)

The web site

has a picture of a scene at the New Inn, Gloucester, just before
letter H, showing a Type 4 waggon in the background and a two-wheeled
cart in the left foreground. I don't know the date of the picture,but
the cart is very like an early 16th century one shown on a map in the
Muniments of Winchester College, MS 3233 (Harvey, Maps in Tudor
England p.17). That notes the names and areas of a number of fields,
and in the foreground is &quot;The hie Wey ledynge from london to
Basyngstoke&quot;. On the highway is a traveller with three pack-horses (he
rides the last; they are not tied together and so evidently know their
way) and another with a two-wheeled cart drawn by a horse. These must
be meant as typical of the traffic between London and Basingstoke. But
I do not know what Taylor would call such a cart.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="

&gt;Allowing for a certain amount of exaggeration, this list
&gt;provides a useful snapshot of the transport system
