Hobson, the Cambridge carrier, hired out horses for riding (on the
principle of Hobson's choice) but his carrying business was wheeled.
From Milton's second poem on his death,
&quot;He di'd for heavines that his Cart went light&quot; (line 22)
&quot;Linkt to the mutual flowing of the Seas,
Yet (strange to think) his wain was his increase&quot; (lines 31-2). (This
would date from Milton's Cambridge period, the 1630s.)
Evidently, you could call someone a carrier all the same, even if he
used wheels.

