If the (traditional and Stratfordian) view was sound
we should see much more evidence of the use of
Latin generally. At the level of ordinary business
done in such a town (or in any city or town) there
is nothing. As regards civic management, there is
nothing -- or next to nothing. Even when you reach
the level of international relations, where frequently
people meet who do not share (or are not comfortable
in) any living language, we find almost no evidence
of the use of Latin -- except occasionally among clerics
and scholarly types.

This is a typical report of the times:
&quot;Throgmorton paid the penalty for his treason at Tyburn. As for
Mendoza, on January 9th [1584] he was invited to meet members
of the Privy Council at the house of the Lord Chancellor. When he
got there he found the Lord Chancellor, the Lord Chamberlain,
Burghley, Leicester, Hunsdon and Walsingham assembled to
meet him. Walsingham, who spoke Italian better than the rest,
addressed him. The Queen, he said, was well aware of Mendoza's
efforts to disturb the peace of her kingdom. She knew all about his
dealings with the disaffected Catholics, with the Scottish Queen
and with those who were planning the invasion of England. She
consequently preferred his room to his company and was
graciously pleased to allow him fifteen days to get out of England. &quot;
(Conyers Read, *Burghley*, page 288)

Mendoza, the Spanish ambassador, did not speak
English (almost inevitably). Clearly none of the Privy
Council were competent in Spanish. Italian was the
next best. Latin was not considered -- even though
all present had, presumably, at one time achieved
grammar school standard (at least) in the language,
and most would have studied it at university or
received private tuition to an equivalent level.

There is the famous occasion in 1597 when the
Queen is supposed to have responded ex tempore in
Latin to an impertinent address in that language from
a Polish ambassador. It's possible, but the report (in
a letter of Robert Cecil's) sounds greatly exaggerated
to my ears.

What I am saying is that Elizabethans probably
studied Latin in much the same way as we did at
school, and allowing for their younger age (7-13) the
standard they achieved would not have been any
better. We learned next to nothing of any 'use',
and soon forgot all we had learned. So why was
the subject studied? I don't know. I suspect that
it is a little like square-bashing in the army. No one
pretends that it is of any real direct use, and no one
knows why it seems to work. But it does -- so it is
continued.

The Stratfordian story that the Stratman acquired
real competence in Latin in the local grammar
school (assuming that he attended) is pure fantasy.

The true author (whoever he was) was certainly
a good Latinist, and competent in several
languages. His education was a world away from
that received in a provincial school with one
(often-changed) master.

Paul.

