It is, in fact, quite easy to work out when LLL
must have been written, and for what occasion
it would have been first performed -- if you know
a little of the international politics between 1575
and 1600, and are aware of how the characters
in LLL are portrayed and who they represent.
(Since the principal ones bear the same names,
they are not hard to guess.)

You finish up with a completely different
understanding of the play -- as against that
portrayed by idiot Stratfordians.

Of course, that is but the start -- the scratching
of the surface. You soon realise that the whole
of the canon might nearly as well be written in
an unknown language for all the comprehension
of it that is passed on to us from the professional
'interpreters' like Germaine Greer.

