There are very few records of the names of *any* actors before
1592, except for the sharers in a few major companies such
as the Queen's Men and Worcester's Men. Over the entire
life of Strange's Men, we only know the names of seven
members of the company for sure -- six from a 1593 touring
patent, and one from a record of a 1591 court payment.
There is absolutely no reason to expect a record of
Shakespeare in the company, given that he presumably
would have been a hired man during that time. Or, if he
did become a sharer with Strange's Men, it's not too
surprising that he wasn't one of the six men named in
the 1593 touring patent, since he was presumably working
on Lucrece during that time.

Look at it this way. The first certain record of Shakespeare
as an actor with a specific company is the 1595 court payment
which shows him as a prominent member of the Lord Chamberlain's
Men. That same record is also the first certain record of
Richard Burbage as an actor, at a time when Burbage was 26 years
old. Why ISN'T there any record of Burbage's acting career
before that time? Hmmmmm??? He suddenly shows up as one
of the leading members of the top acting company in London,
and he's soon vying with Edward Alleyn for the title of
best actor in England, and there's no record of him acting
before 1595? You can't be serious! There must be some
conspiracy at work here. Or, hey, it could just be that
there are very few records of specific actors before that time.

