A closer look at the probable per rider costs:

It'd have been around a 200 mile journey, so the
posthorse transportation costs per person
on the Hentzner London-Cambridge-Oxford-London
route would have been around 2l 10s. Doing
the 90 miles between Cambridge and Oxford
in one day would have been fairly
extraordinary, so they'd probably have
spent at least one night in some inn between
those two towns.

From everything I've read, a good horse
can fairly easily do 30 miles for several
days in a row, so if the Hentzner party
had hired horses, they'd probably have
overnighted once between London and
Cambridge, twice between Cambridge and
Oxford, and once between Oxford and
London. (That's three more nights in
inns outside a &quot;big&quot; city than they'd
have spent if they'd ridden post.) All
told, it's 7 days travel. If we suppose
that they wanted to spend a week in Cambridge
and a week in London, the charge per
person for a hired horse should have been
around 4s 2d. Subtracting that from
2l 10s, leaves 2l 5s 10p. I am not sure
what it cost to feed a horse for three
weeks, but I doubt it was as much as
the cost of the hire. Even if it were
so much, that'd still leave the traveler
with better than 2 pounds savings. I can't
imagine there were many country inns where
the charge was anything close to 13s per night.

