Or maybe not.

Up until the turn of the 16th century, at
least, coach travel was looked on as somewhat
effeminate. I think the implication in
that is that it was seen as &quot;easy&quot;. Inside
the coach, one was quite protected from the
elements. Sleep was possible. Travel
at night was easier. (Well, not for the
coachman.) Bringing a fair amount of
luggage becomes reasonable.

The postmasters had monopolies and their
charges per mile were independent of the
quality of the horse they lent out. That
being so, it is not too surprising that
there were a fair number of people who
complained about the inferior quality
of the posthorses they were issued.
If a foreign noble had good connections
at Court, they might well receive the
best a stable could offer, but you've
been assuming that Hentzner's patron
was generally treated like dirt. Needless
to say, if he was wealthy enough to ride
post, he could rather easily have hired
an extremely fine horse.

Additionally, if the roads were quite bad,
the advantage of riding post would be
pretty much nullified. (The danger of
the horse putting a hoof in a pothole would
presumably be enough keep the rider traveling
at a slower rate.)

One of the problems faced by Hentzner's noble,
is that if he rode post, he'd probably have
had to obtain a horse for each member of his
retinue. (Not many servants can trot along
at 7 or 8 miles an hour for a large part
of a day.) Assuming that he travelled with
luggage commensurate with his station, he'd
probably have had to hire a couple of post
horses just for that.

