Commercial brewing became big in the 18th to 19th centuries. Brewing
ale was known to the Egyptians. Brewing in Britain is referred to by
Roman sources. Ale seems to have become the sole national drink under
the Anglo-Saxons. Later some people started to brew in larger
quantities to supplement home brewing. The Domesday book records 43
brewers. The Brewery of Queen's College Oxford was founded in 1340 and
lasted until 1939. In 1267 Henry III introduced the Assize of Bread
and Ale. Beer was not brewed until the 16th century as the
introduction of hopped ale was resisted.

